<div id="review_3679972203" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3679972203" />
    <a title="Denton Peter McCabe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40430150-denton-peter-mccabe"><img alt="Denton Peter McCabe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600929843p2/40430150.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3679972203?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Denton Peter McCabe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Denton Peter McCabe" href="/user/show/40430150-denton-peter-mccabe">Denton Peter McCabe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781847399243" href="/book/show/8153471-of-saints-and-shadows">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3679972203" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18421519692771586109">SPOILERS:<br/><br/>Well, somewhat of a spoiler. So stop reading. <br/><br/>The conflict in this book, between Peter, and this Catholic Church, which is part Inquisition, part shadowy occultist syndicate, is not only far fetched but it presents the reader with an attempt to shoehorn this atheistic fantasy about organized religion being the ultimate Evil into this story line. The catalyst, the murder mystery that the book begins with, did very little to draw the reader into the conflict, and the character of Peter be</span>
  <span id="freeText18421519692771586109" style="display:none">SPOILERS:<br /><br />Well, somewhat of a spoiler. So stop reading. <br /><br />The conflict in this book, between Peter, and this Catholic Church, which is part Inquisition, part shadowy occultist syndicate, is not only far fetched but it presents the reader with an attempt to shoehorn this atheistic fantasy about organized religion being the ultimate Evil into this story line. The catalyst, the murder mystery that the book begins with, did very little to draw the reader into the conflict, and the character of Peter becomes this awkwardly redeemable vampire. He doesn't kill. He only drinks the blood of the already dead. From morgues. With the help of an accomplice. The story took a serious nosedive into ethical sanguinariansm at that point. <br /><br />Perhaps the author made too much of an attempt to paint the vampire as noble and the Catholics as barbaric, while occasionally pausing to reflect on whether or not there really is a god. In this philosophical inversion, the protagonist becomes a squeaky clean ascetic vampire, one who has renounced his barbarism, his bloodlust, and the church meanwhile allows itself to become drunk on the blood of the martyrs. The plot is tedious at best, and despite some rather vivid and imaginative murder scenes, this was not the book I expected. <br /><br />I'd recommend this for teenagers if anything. Two stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18421519692771586109" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


